Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you donâ€™t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Liechtenstein. The Liechtenstein authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Anyone who wishes to leave Liechtenstein should contact their travel operator to make the arrangements to do so as soon as possible. See Return to the UK.
Gatherings of more than 5 people are banned. This applies to all public and private events, including religious services. All restaurants, bars, leisure and entertainment facilities are closed. All educational establishments are also closed. Those aged over 65 or with pre-existing medical conditions are encouraged to stay at home.
The border with Switzerland remains open. However, the border crossings at Schellenberg and Mauren are closed. The border crossings at Ruggell and Schaanwald remain open for commuters, goods traffic and transit. Further restrictions and inspections may be in operation.
The Government has announced that all shops and markets will reopen from Monday 27 April, and that hospitals and medical practioners (including dentists) can resume all non-urgent treatment. You can find more information on the emergency measures in place on the Government website (in German).
You may also wish to check our Travel Advice for Switzerland and Austria.
If you believe you have symptoms, you should not go directly to the hospital or a healthcare facility. Instead you should call the coronavirus emergency number on +423 235 45 32 (24 hours).
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
